US Flights 2018 Dataset¶

by Islam M. Saad¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

US Flights 2018 Dataset contains about 7.2 million observations and 27 variables. There are 16 Airlines operating Carriers, which facilitate US flights in 2018.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

7.2 million records dataset and we will use random sample of 10% (about 720K) records in order to ease and agile the analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Arrival Delay, Departure Delay

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

OP_CARRIER, Actual Elapsed Time, ORIGIN Airports, DEST Airports, Distance, DATE, Arrival Time, Departure Time.

Cleaning Dataset¶

We will find out not cancelled flights to be only included in df

In [7]:
#we will make new df with cancelled equals 0
df['CANCELLED'].value_counts()
Out[7]:
0.0    709718
1.0     11627
Name: CANCELLED, dtype: int64

Then we have 11627 cancelled flights from 10% sample of 7.2Million Records and then we will drop it as we only study delay of flights.

In [8]:
#creat new data frame called flights with Non-cancelled flights 7,096,862 observations
flights = df.query("CANCELLED==0")
flights.shape
Out[8]:
(709718, 29)

#cleaning our dataset by finding out duplicated rows
flights.duplicated().sum()
Out[9]:

In [10]:
#cleaning our dataset by drop duplicated 34387 rows
flights=flights.drop_duplicates()
flights.shape
Out[10]:
(675331, 29)

We found 34387 duplicated rows in flights dataframe and after drop it, we have 675331 records at our 10% sample.

Contniue - Cleaning Dataset¶

We have important columns having missing values such as: 'DEP_DELAY','WHEELS_ON','TAXI_IN','ARR_TIME','ARR_DELAY','CRS_ELAPSED_TIME','ACTUAL_ELAPSED_TIME','AIR_TIME' we will delete only rows with missing data on those columns Additionally, we have columns have huge misisng data but we don't need to lose all these rows such as: 'SECURITY_DELAY','NAS_DELAY','LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY','WEATHER_DELAY','CARRIER_DELAY' because those rows can reflect the reason for delay as we can expecte right now. Furthermore, 'CANCELLED','CANCELLATION_CODE', 'Unnamed' have approximately no data to help, and then we will drop them.

In [12]:
flights.drop(['CANCELLED','CANCELLATION_CODE','Unnamed: 27'],axis='columns', inplace=True)
flights.shape
Out[12]:
(675331, 26)

# Convert string to DateTime
pd.to_datetime(flights.FL_DATE)

In [16]:
# ARRIVAL DELAY Minutes to hours 
flights['ARR_DELAY_HR'] = flights['ARR_DELAY'] / 60
# DEPARTURE DELAY Minutes to hours 
flights['DEP_DELAY_HR'] = flights['DEP_DELAY'] / 60

In [20]:
# univariate plots of ARRIVAL DELAY
ARR_order = flights['ARR_DELAY_FLAG'].value_counts().index
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data=flights, x='ARR_DELAY_FLAG', color=base_color, order=ARR_order);
plt.xticks(rotation=0);
# Recalculating the cut_counts
ARR_DELAY_counts = flights['ARR_DELAY_FLAG'].value_counts()
# Returns the sum of all not-null values in `cut` column
n_flights = flights['ARR_DELAY_FLAG'].value_counts().sum()
# get the current tick locations and labels
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=0) 

# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = ARR_DELAY_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.2f}%'.format(100*count/n_flights)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black',fontsize=15, verticalalignment='baseline')
plt.xlabel('Flights ARRIVAL TIME DELAYED');
plt.ylabel('Count');
from matplotlib import rcParams
# Specify the figure size in inches, for both X, and Y axes
rcParams['figure.figsize'] =4,4

In [53]:
xbin_edges = np.arange(-117, flights['ARR_DELAY'].max()+150, 150)
ybin_edges = np.arange(-109,    flights['DEP_DELAY'].max()+120, 120)

# count number of points in each bin
xbin_idxs = pd.cut(flights['ARR_DELAY'], xbin_edges, right = False,
                    include_lowest = True, labels = False).astype(int)
ybin_idxs = pd.cut(flights['DEP_DELAY'], ybin_edges, right = False,
                    include_lowest = True, labels = False).astype(int)

pts_per_bin = flights.groupby([xbin_idxs, ybin_idxs]).size()
pts_per_bin = pts_per_bin.reset_index()
pts_per_bin = pts_per_bin.pivot(index = 'ARR_DELAY', columns = 'DEP_DELAY').values

z_wts = flights['DISTANCE'] / pts_per_bin[xbin_idxs, ybin_idxs]

# plot the data using the calculated weights
plt.hist2d(data = flights, x = 'ARR_DELAY', y = 'DEP_DELAY', weights = z_wts,
           bins = [xbin_edges, ybin_edges], cmap = 'viridis_r', cmin = 0.5);
plt.title("Arrival Delay & Departure Delay & Flight Distance Relationship")
plt.xlabel('ARR_DELAY in minutes')
plt.ylabel('DEP_DELAY in minutes');
plt.colorbar(label = 'mean(DISTANCE) in Miles');
  • We can find oyu that Arrival Delay & Departure Delay is very small for long average distant trips (more than 2000 Miles). We can also see small distant flight trip took larger delay tahn medium distant trips.
